      {
        "id": 277701,
        "name": "Talya (she/her)",
        "username": "rassilon1963",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/rassilon1963/{size}/31625_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-10-21T11:21:29.003Z",
        "cooked": "<p>while this might be a more aesthetically pleasing design, i think it’ll be worse for the user in terms of actually understanding what this slider does.<br>\nPN discoverability and PN sharing are two fundementally different properties. in theory one could even decide (via a custom client) to have the fourth combination disallowed by Signal. the reason it’s disallowed is it’s unclear what its use would be, and that it could cause issues with the Contact Discovery Service. but in principle one could do it, since those are two different things.<br>\ni think that it’s good the settings are separated, since they serve different purposes - one is about divulging information, the other is about what to do with people who already have that information. the two also deserve different titles and different explanations attached.<br>\nyou also don’t want to create a design situation where to discover what all the settings do one needs to slide across them (since those settings can have serious security implications), but with a slider you have three options: either include the full explanation text for each level next to it, which looks horrible, include all the text below the slider which leads to people not reading it, or only include the text for the selected setting, which encourages people to test all settings out (and potentially leaking sensitive information).</p>",
